= Litho
*Did you learn anything from seeing the attempt to build a basic lithography
system? What was the biggest insight from seeing EUV source development and the
challenges ASML needed to overcome?*

I think together these videos illistrate the nessisity of lithography and the importance of process control.

In the first video, I was supprised with how quickly a initial version of the machine came together. This is very impressive and is infulenced by the high avaliableity of information and the lack of need for fundamental research. The many challenges of the video are getting the machine(s) within spec. This real world example shows how once a plan is made, there is very little physics in the way of making a tool; the main challenge are of the variety of ensuring the device is place on a level surface.

The ASML video acts as the opposit version of that in showing how hard it can be to make a plan for a device. There is a ton of fundamental research that is a part of this done over many decades. The main two components being the x-ray mirrors and the a reliable light source. Once a outline is made the rest is becomes an implementation problem. Granted the problems become signifigently more complexity such as managing the tin particles cleaning and a laser heating method. It is not shown in the video but there was most likely a long process of doing process control as well.

I think this shows the importance of how academic and engineering research intersect as both require the other in many ways. Feasibilty studies need to be based on theory and real implementations bring up new problems that need to be researched.
